data.title: Traces of Evil: Remaining Nazi Sites in Westphalia (3)
data.meta_description: Remaining Nazi sites then and now
data.text:
During the war Ibbenbren had at least twelve hospitals, in many of which considerable wounded had to be taken from field hospitals. According to the memory of former Wehrbeauftragter of the German Bundestag, Karl-Wilhelm Berkhan,

I had severe gallbladder inflammation, and I came from Westerkappeln to Ibbenbren to a hospital that had once been a Catholic hospital, fortunately. Nuns cared for us, and there were still good doctors there, though in uniform, but experienced in the medical arts; experts in diagnosis and therapy. An older doctor, but only medical officer in the rank, took care of me. He advised against an operation, since the Allies had already crossed the Rhine.
